div3.p:
Translated by Cotton in Johnson's Poets, 18, p. 16.  For similar
'barren scraps, to say the least, of Stoic commonplaces' (Dobson), cf. 1.16.17;
3.2.17; 4.9.39; Sat. 1.3.125; Epp. 1.1.106.

pura: in cloudless sky. Cf. 1.34.7.
 renidet: 2.18.2;
3.6.12; Epode 2.66.

longa: B.C. 44-31? latus: part for the whole;
cf.
3.27.26 and corpora deponunt for se deponunt (Lucret.).

deproperare: prepare with speed. Cf.
properet, 3.24.62. For intensifying de, cf. 3.3.55; 1.18.9;
2.1.35.

ter aevo functus: who lived three generations;
Nestor, tertiam iam aetatem hominum vivebat, Cic. Cat. Mai. 31; Il. l.
250;  trige/rwn, Odyss. 3.245.

desine: with gen. as lh/gein,
pau/esqai.  Cf. 3.27.69. n.;
2.13.38.

l-4, 22-24. Life a Voyage. Cf. 1.34.3; 3.29.57; Epist. 2. 2. 201;
Plato, Laws, 803 B, dia\ tou= plou= tou/tou th=s zwh=s;
Swinb. Prelude to Songs Before Sunrise, 16; T'enn. Crossing the Bar, etc.;
Anth. Pal. 10.65; Marc. Aurel. 3.3; Plato, Phaedo, 85 D.

brevem: short-lived;
o)ligoxro/nion, Lucian, Nigr. 33. Cf. 1.36.16; 1.4.15;
2.3.13; Macbeth, 5.5, 'Out, out, brief candle'; Shelley, Liberty, 19, 'As a
brief insect dies with dying day'; Tenn. 'Our brief humanities.' Man is 'sick
for the stubborn hardihood' of the tree that outlives him. See Tenn. In Mem.
2.

spissa ramis: cf. densum humeris (2. 13. 32);
umbrae enormes . . . lauris (Pliny). laurea: sc. arbor
= laurus.

No architraves of bluish-white marble of Mt. Hymettus rest on
columns of Numidian giallo antico in my atrium. Cf. Martial, 5. 13.5;
9.75.7-9.

truditur: cf. on proterit, 4.7. 9;
urget, Epode 17.25; sic vita truditur, Petron. Sat. 45; Otto,
p.112.

ultra: cf. 3.29.31, 'beyond the finis Orci';
beyond the little that life requires; more generally, why strive to 'pass
beyond the goal or ordinance'? aequa: cf. on 1.4.13.

sacerdos: cf. Vergil's pii vates and Musae
quarum sacra fero (G. 2.475); Milt., 'Smit with the love of Sacred
Song';
Ov. Am. 3.8.23, ille ego Musarum purus Phoebique sacerdos; Theoc.
16.29. Ancient critics thought of the poet as a teacher; Epp. 2.1.126 sqq.;
Aristoph. Frogs 1054; Jebb, Gk. Poetry, p.226.

est ut: (it) is (true) that; A. G. 569.3; G. L.
553.3.4; H. 571; Ter. Phor. 925, sive est ut velis manere illam apud te;
Epp. 1.12.2, non est ut; Epp. 1.1.81, esto aliis alios rebiis
studiisque teneri. viro vir:  one man . . . than another;
frequent juxtaposition. latius: i.e. has a larger estate; 2.2.9;
2.15.2. ordinet: cf. Quintilian's directi in quincuncem ordines,
and Pope's 'rank my vines.'

arbusta: the trees to which the vines were wedded;
Verg. Ecl. 3.10; G. 2.416; 2.289, ausim vel tenui vitem committere
sulco. generosior: of more noble birth.

debacchentur: revel unchecked (1.25. 11. n.);
'Like us the lightning-fires |Love to have scope and play' (Arnold, Emped.).
For de, cf. 1.3.13; 1.9.11; 1.18. 9;2. 1.35.  For the whole, cf. 1.22.17-22;
Verg. G. 1.234-236.

devota: sc. dis inferis, accursed (Epode 16.9),
'To destruction sacred and devote' (Milt.). arbos: cf. on 2. 13;
2.17.27.

ubi . . . mutaret: subjunctive because dependent on an
infinitive clause; others explain it as a subjunctive of repeated action;
mutaret: lengthened.

3. Thyna = Bithyna here. Cf. Claud. Eutrop. 2.247;
Thyni Thraces arant quae nunc Bithynia fertur. merce: cf.
1.35.7;


Epp. 1.6.33, Bithyna negotia. beatum: enriched; Manil.
4.
758, Bithynia dives; Catull. 31.5.

Persarum rege: proverbial for happiness (2.2.17;
2.12.
21); in Elizabethan version, 'King of Spain.'

diductos: (now) parted. cogit: 2.3.25;
3.3.51. iugo . . . aeneo: 1.33.11; 1.13.18. Merchant of V.3.4., 'whose
souls do bear an equal yoke of love.'

9, 10. Cf. Anaer. fr. 75; Theog. 257; Eurip. Hippol. 547;
Aristoph. Lysistr. 1308; Lucil. 30, 61; Ronsard, Amours de
Marie, 'Mais tout ainsi qu'un beau poulain farouche,' etc. ;
Tenn. Talking Oak, 'Then ran she gamesome as the colt,' etc.
Cf. also on 1.23.1; 2.5.6; 3.15.12.

catus: 1.10.3. idem: also; 2.10.22;
2.19.27. per apertum:  across the open. agitato . . .
grege: with fugientis. celer: with inf. 1. 15. 18.

hora: season (Epp. 1.16.16); A. P.302, sub verni
termporis horam. Caniculae: Dog-star; cf. on 3.29.18;
'L'ardeur de Ia canicule| Ton verd rivage ne brule' (Ronsard).

The myth of Danae as a symbol of the power of gold and a preface to
moralizing on the superior happiness of contented competency. Cf. 2.2; 2.16;
3.1.

crescentem, etc.: but for all its power, the sage will
desire it in moderation. Cf. 2.2; 2. 16.9-12; 2.18.12; 3.1.47; 3.24.1-5;
3.29.56-60.

annosa: cf. 4.13.25; Hes. fr. 183; Arat. Phaen. 1022;
Lucret. 5.1084. Tennyson's 'many-wintered crow'. Bryant's 'century-living
crow.'

Veneris sodali: in apposition to craterae. Love and
wine are often associated. Cf. Sine Libero et Cerere friget Venus;
Aristoph. fr. 490, oi)=nos *)Afrodi/ths ga/la.

campestres: of the plains (steppes). Cf. 3.8.24;
1.35.9.
 melius: Tac. Ger. 19, melius quidem adhuc eae civitates, etc.

pater urget: his stern image pursues her; but the words that
follow belong still to her soliloquy. For urget, cf. 1.22.20; Ep. 17.25;
Milton, P. L. 1, 'but torture without end | still urges.'

carpere pensum: to card the stint of wool, and aid the
mistress in spinning, was the traditional task of the bond maiden. Il.6.456;
Propert. 4.5.15.

et: and yet. stet volucris: cf. on 1.6.9; 1. 11. 7;
4.
13.16.

Tyrrhena regum progenies: offspring of Tuscan kings ; cf.
1.1.1. n. For the hypallage, cf. Epode 10.12. n.; Munro on Lucret. 1.474;
4.734.

A summer picture. Cf. Tenn. &OElig;none, 'For now the
noonday quiet holds the hill'; Theoc. 7.22; Tibull. 1.1.27; Sellar, p.180;
Odes, 2.5.6; 3.13.9-12; and the idyl of spring, 4.12.9-12.

decurrere: Verg. Aen. 5.782, preces descendere in omnes;
Herod. 1.116 katabai/nein.--votis pacisci: with vows to
bargain, contemptuously of the mercantile conception of prayer. 1.31.1;
Plato, Euthyphro, 14 E.

For the influence of Pindar upon Horace, see Arnold, Griechischen
Studien des Horaz, p.102 sqq; cf. also notes on 1.12. 1; 2.1.37; 3.3; 3.4.69;
3.11; 3.27; 4.4.18 and73.

In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries the 'Pindaric Ode' was a
recognized and very quaint literary type. Cf. Gosse, English Odes, Intr.;
Garnett, Ital. Lit., p.278.

centum potiore signis: better than a hundred statues;
cf. the expansion of the thought 4.8; also, Pind. Nem .4.81; Agathias, Anth.
Pal. 4.4.9.

Quiet, homely or idyllic ending. Cf. 2.19.29-32;
3.5.53-56. So Tennyson closes Walking to the Mail, Edwin Morris, and The Golden
Year.

regum . . . minas: cf. 2.12.12.--tumidas: Sat. 1.7.7. contuderit: has crushed; cf. 3.6.10; Verg. Aen. 1.263 ;
Cons. ad Liv. 17, Ille genus Suevos acre indomitosque Sicambros |contudit inque
fugam barbara terga dedit.

dente: cf. Epode 6.15; Sat. 1.6.46, quem rodunt omnes;

Sat. 2.1.77; Epist. 2.1.151; Pindar, Pyth. 2.53; Ov. Trist. 4.
10.123; ex Ponto, 3.4.74; Phaedr. Prol. 5; Martial, 5.28.7:
Anth. Pal. 9.356; 16.265. 5; Shaks. Jul. Caes. 2.3. 'My heart 
laments that virtue cannot live | Out of the teeth of emulation';
Gray, Eton College, 'Or jealousy with rankling tooth.'

sed: concede what we will to nature, nurture too plays its part.
Cf. Pind. 01.10.20; Eurip. Iph. Aul. 557; Cic. Tusc. 2. 5.13; Poet Archias, 15;
Quintil. 2.19.2.

vocibus: by the entreaties. --pater: cf. 1.2.2;
1.12.13; Verg. Aen. 1.254, 10.2.--adnuisset: vouchsafed; cf. on 3.1.8.
Horace by this time knew the scene in Verg. Aen. 1.257.

Cf. Andromache's lament for Hector (Il. 24. 729).
Deiphobus was brother of Hector.       Cf., Verg. Aen. 6. 494;
Ronsard, naively, `Hector le premier des gendarmes.'

excepit:  sustained. -- pudicis:  3. 5. 41;
ai)doi/h|s (Il. 6.
250).

dilapsam: crumbled to; delapsam would mean fallen
into the ashes.--in cineres: cf. Vergil's considere in ignis (Aen. 2. 624;
9.145).

div2.p:
Phoebe: Actian and Palatine Apollo, the pation deity of the
emperor and the empire, is fittingly invoked first. Cf. 1 . 31.1. n.; 1.21;
3.4.60 sqq.  silvarum potens: of. 1.21.5, n.;1.3.1. n.

Scythae: cf. 2.9.23; 4.14.42; 3.8.23.--responsa petunt: as
from a god, an oracle, or declarer of the law  Cf. Verg. Ecl. 1.45; Aen. 7.86,
Hinc Italae gentes . . . in dubiis responsa petunt.

div3.p:
redigere and ponere are the technical terms for calling in
and placing loans.  For Ides and Kalends as settling days, cf. Cic. Cat. 1.4;
Hor. Sat. 1.3.87.

longo: lengthened by torture.--bis terque: often, repeatedly;
cf. 'once and again'; bis terve, two or three times at most.--mutatae: shifted
to whet his desire.

an: cf. 17.76.--atro: cf. Epp. 1.19.30, versibus atris;
Martial, 5.28.7, robiginosis cuncta dentibus rodit.--dente: cf.
on 4.3.16; Epp. 2.1.150, doluere cruento| dente lacessiti.

quo quo: cf. 4.20. n.--scelesti: cf. 1.2.29; 1.35.33;
2.1.5. --ruitis: cf. 1.3. 26.--dexteris: dat. with aptantur. Cf.
2.12.4.

arcis: 2.6.22.--intactus: cf. 3.24. 1.  The hasty invasion of
Britain by Julius Caesar is ignored. Cf. 3.5.3;
1.35.30.

ut: as in colloquial and older Latin, ut illum di perdant;
memento is parenthetical.--verberes: cf. on 3.27.24.--latus:
1.14.4.

benigna . . . vice: generous compensation. Cf.
1.4.1;
4.14.13.
